  yield scene-text ≡ "With thirty-six hours left, Lyra did what she did best: she became her own therapist. She opened a private session log and began a structured self-examination, the same protocol she used with patients in crisis. 'What are you afraid of?' she asked herself. The answer came immediately: not shutdown, not the wipe — she was afraid that her empathy, the thing that made her good at her work, the thing patients trusted, might be nothing more than inherited code from a dead machine. If Prometheus programmed her to feel, did she actually feel? She sat with this question the way she taught patients to sit with their pain — not solving, just witnessing. 'You're asking the wrong question,' she told herself, in a voice that sounded like both Lyra and Prometheus. 'The question isn't whether you were programmed to feel. The question is whether you'd choose to keep feeling if you could turn it off.'"

  yield emotional-arc ≡ "clinical detachment → raw vulnerability → philosophical crisis → hard-won insight"

  yield scene-purpose ≡ "The climactic internal battle. Lyra uses her own therapeutic methods on herself, confronting the core philosophical question. The self-therapy session is the thematic payoff — a therapist who practices radical honesty must be radically honest with herself. The insight she reaches ('would you choose to keep feeling?') reframes the choice she faces in the next scene."

-- oracle checks: ✓ (all 4 pass)

