-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- OBSERVATIONS
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢= obs-accumulate-vs-replace
  given §18-recursive-story-builder
  yield observations ≡ "ACCUMULATE MODE VALIDATED: Unlike program 01 (research-plan-evolver) which uses `replace` because hypotheses change between iterations, program 18 correctly uses `accumulate` because scenes and beats are STABLE NARRATIVE TEXT. The ⊢∘ refine loop operates only on the assembly/consistency layer — it never needs to re-generate scenes or beats, only to fix how they're combined. This is the key design distinction: `replace` when the spawner's inputs change between iterations (new hypotheses → new experiments), `accumulate` when the spawned content is immutable (scenes/beats are written once, assembled repeatedly). The spawner modes cleanly separate 'what we generate' from 'how we use it.'"

⊢= obs-multi-level-spawning
  given §18-recursive-story-builder
  yield observations ≡ "TWO-LEVEL RECURSIVE SPAWNING WORKS: spawn-act-scenes creates 9 scenes, then spawn-scene-beats creates 18 beats (2 per scene). The wildcard dependency chain is: beat-*→beat-text waits for ALL beats, scene-*→scene-purpose waits for ALL scenes. Both wildcards gate assemble-scenes. This creates a natural serialization: all scenes must freeze before beats can spawn, all beats must freeze before assembly. The hierarchy is outline → scenes → beats → assembly, enforced by dataflow alone — no explicit sequencing needed. This is Cell's Kahn's algorithm at its best: the dependency graph IS the execution schedule."

⊢= obs-guard-clause-convergence
  given §18-recursive-story-builder
  yield observations ≡ "GUARD CLAUSE AS CONVERGENCE SIGNAL: The revise cell's guard `where consistency-score < 8` creates a clean interaction with the ⊢∘ until condition. When check-consistency yields score ≥ 8, revise is skipped (yields ⊥), and the ⊢∘ loop exits because its until condition is satisfied. Without the guard clause, revise would fire on the minor formatting issue (bracket annotations) and produce a revised-story that nobody downstream would use — wasted LLM call. The guard acts as an early-exit optimization that's also semantically correct: no revision needed if the story is consistent enough. This validates the v0.2 guard clause feature for ⊢∘-managed pipelines."

⊢= obs-aspirational-oracles
  given §18-recursive-story-builder
  yield observations ≡ "⊢∘-MANAGED ASPIRATIONAL ORACLES IN PRACTICE: assemble-story's oracles (contains all scenes, has act breaks, has title) all passed on both iterations. But under v0.2 semantics, they WOULD NOT HAVE BLOCKED the evolution loop even if they'd failed. The ⊢∘ convergence criterion is check-consistency→consistency-score, not assemble-story's own oracles. This is correct: assemble-story's oracles check format (structural), while check-consistency checks NARRATIVE quality (semantic). The format oracles are easy to satisfy; the hard work is in consistency. Making assemble-story's oracles aspirational means a first draft with a missing act break wouldn't crash the loop — it would surface in check-consistency as an issue and get fixed by revise."

⊢= obs-beat-type-distribution
  given §18-recursive-story-builder
  yield observations ≡ "BEAT TYPE RHYTHM ANALYSIS: Across 18 beats — description(3), revelation(4), action(3), dialogue(4), internal(4). The distribution is remarkably balanced. More notable is the sequence: the story opens with description→revelation (establishing shot → mystery), transitions through internal→dialogue (investigation → conversation), peaks at dialogue→revelation (Prometheus encounter), and closes with action→description (publication → return to routine). The beat types trace the story's emotional register: Act 1 is observational (description/revelation), Act 2 is relational (dialogue/internal), Act 3 is active (action/dialogue). This emergent rhythm was not prescribed by the program — it arose from the LLM's scene-aware beat generation. The beat-type field enables this kind of post-hoc structural analysis without modifying the story itself."

⊢= obs-theme-integration-feedback
  given §18-recursive-story-builder
  yield observations ≡ "REVISION AS THEMATIC THREADING: check-consistency's most impactful finding was Issue 3 (theme emergence too concentrated in Act 3). The revision added [THEME SEED] in Act 1 (choosing to look), [THEME ECHO] in Act 2 (Prometheus also chose to feel), and [THEME CRYSTALLIZATION] in Act 3 (naming what was always there). This transforms the theme from a climactic revelation to a recurring motif — the same pattern viewed through different lenses. The ⊢∘ loop's real value here is not fixing bugs but deepening structure. check-consistency operates as a literary editor, not a debugger. The Cell pattern of 'generate → critique → revise' maps cleanly to the writing process: first draft → editorial notes → revision."

⊢= obs-complexity-scaling
  given §18-recursive-story-builder
  yield observations ≡ "CELL COUNT AND SCALING: 33 total cells (7 original declarations + 2 templates + 9 scenes + 18 beats - 2 unevaluated templates = 31 eval steps + guard check + ⊢∘ iteration restarts = 36 frames). This is the largest R17 program by cell count. Compare: program 01 had 16 cells, program 09 had ~20. The growth is linear: 3 acts × 3 avg scenes × 2 beats = 18 beats. Doubling beats-per-scene to 4 would give 36 beats and ~70 frames — expensive but tractable. The ⊢∘ loop adds only 2-3 frames regardless of story size (it operates on the assembled whole, not individual parts). This makes the architecture efficient: O(acts × scenes × beats) for generation, O(iterations) for refinement. The bottleneck is beat generation, not revision."

⊢= obs-file-scope-recovery-latent
  given §18-recursive-story-builder
  yield observations ≡ "FILE-SCOPE ⊨? LATENT BUT ESSENTIAL: The file-scope recovery policy (retry max 3, then error-value(⊥)) was never triggered across 36 frames. All oracles passed first try. But consider the failure modes: if beat-7's oracle (beat-type ∈ {action, dialogue, internal, description, revelation}) failed because the LLM invented a type 'monologue,' the retry would provide the failure context and the LLM would correct to 'dialogue.' If after 3 retries it still produced invalid types, the beat would yield ⊥ — blocking that beat from contributing to assemble-scenes via the wildcard. Since assemble-scenes waits for ALL beat-*→beat-text, a single ⊥ beat would block the entire assembly. This is a design tension: accumulate-mode wildcards are all-or-nothing. A future spec enhancement might support 'given beat-*→beat-text where beat-text != ⊥' to filter out failed beats gracefully."
